{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"25310477-7564-47f0-83c6-d75af7dc43de","content":"The directory appears empty, so I'll answer from knowledge:\n\nTo switch from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform with MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0, you just need to **remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n    <!-- Remove or set to false: -->\n    <!-- <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest> -->\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n1. **MSTest.Sdk 3.4+** uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform **by default** — `UseVSTest` was opting you back into the legacy runner.\n2. After removing it, run tests with `dotnet test` as usual (it auto-detects the new platform).\n3. If you use `dotnet test` with solution filters or custom `.runsettings`, review them — some VSTest-specific settings (e.g., `RunConfiguration/TestAdaptersPaths`) no longer apply.\n4. Extensions like code-coverage or TRX reporting now use NuGet packages (e.g., `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`, `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage`) instead of command-line switches.\n\nThat single property removal is the only required change when already on MSTest.Sdk 3.8.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"039f2fbe-9f31-435e-962a-9fe106ed713d","outputTokens":353,"requestId":"8432:1C9498:1E5DF67:21AFC5D:6A0ACEA1"},"id":"7f9f0a5d-5919-44d1-8712-e3e649b95de0","timestamp":"2026-05-18T08:32:43.324Z","parentId":"971c2dce-1962-4d75-80a6-8632e6c1dfb0"}
